Modeling Belief Distributions in Prediction Markets¶

Let the latent belief distribution over event probability $p \in [0, 1]$ be:

$$ B(p) \sim \text{Beta}(\alpha, \beta) $$

Observed Beliefs via Microstructure Filtering¶

We do not observe $B(p)$ directly. Instead, we observe a filtered version:

$$ \tilde{B}(p) \propto B(p) \cdot (1 - \rho(p)) $$

where $\rho(p) \in [0, 1]$ is a rejection probability due to market microstructure (e.g., execution, spread, depth).

Parametrizing the Rejection Function¶

We model $\rho(p)$ as a normalized Beta distribution:

$$ \rho(p) = \frac{\text{Beta}(p; \alpha', \beta')}{\max_{q \in [0,1]} \text{Beta}(q; \alpha', \beta')} $$

Parametrizing the Rejection Function¶

We define the rejection probability as a normalized Beta density:

$$ \rho(p) = \frac{\text{Beta}(p; \alpha', \beta')}{\max_{q \in [0,1]} \text{Beta}(q; \alpha', \beta')} $$

The shape parameters $\alpha'$ and $\beta'$ are controlled by two levers:

1. Total Sharpness (Spread Width):

Let

$$ s = \text{spread\_width} > 0 $$

Then set the total precision:

$$ \alpha' + \beta' = \kappa \cdot s $$

where $\kappa > 0$ is a fixed base precision (e.g., 10).

2. Skew:

Let

$$ \delta = \text{skew} \in (-0.5, 0.5) $$

Then allocate:

$$ \alpha' = (\alpha' + \beta') \cdot (0.5 - \delta) \\ \beta' = (\alpha' + \beta') \cdot (0.5 + \delta) $$

Interpretation:

  • $ s \uparrow \Rightarrow $ tighter, sharper rejection zone
  • $ \delta > 0 \Rightarrow $ rejection skewed right (ask-heavy)
  • $ \delta < 0 \Rightarrow $ rejection skewed left (bid-heavy)
